    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="25"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d25">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.6363/11–1044</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Director of the Office of Near Eastern and
                        African Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stettinius</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-23">November 23,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Stettinius</hi>: As you may perhaps have noticed from
                    airgram no. 74 of November 10 from our Minister at Jidda, King Ibn Saud
                    “consented readily” to permit the survey of a possible pipe-line route to the
                        Mediterranean<note n="42" xml:id="d25fn42">In a memorandum of November 25 in
                        reply the Under Secretary of State said that he had noted favorably the
                        King’s consent to permit a survey of a possible pipe-line route across Saudi
                        Arabia.</note> by the Arabian American Oil Company during a visit of
                    officials of that company to Riyadh last month.</p>
                <pb facs="0048" n="36" xml:id="pg_36"/>
                <p>This is good news and a further indication that the King is disposed to play ball
                    with us in everything that pertains to the development of our great oil
                    concession in his country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace Murray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
